76561198079081172,Recommended,433280,20868326,"Posted: 31 January, 2016",all,Jimmy777777,"This brings back memories.I never got to play Warlords Battlecry 3, but I did play the first one extensively when I was a little kid. I enjoyed the combat mechanics to a degree and loved the idea of retaining troops and a hero after each map. This game brings more of the same and then some. That is to say, the same sprites that were used in the first and second games make an appearance here in the third game as well.The leveling mechanic in Warlords Battlecry 3 is done right. Your hero gains experience as the match goes on and can even level during the match (something that could not be done in the first one). Tons of classes and races allow for moderate choices which can dramatically alter your game play.The varying abilities that are available for warlords to take can alter everything. Abilities like Engineer make your building have more hp (think tower defense), while merchant lowers the price of all units universally (good for swarm tactics). Abilities like constitution make warrior warlords a pain, while specific classes such as pyromancy can make enemy warlords dangerous. A well built warlord can take down an army in the blink of an eye, as long you carefully watch the battle unfold.If the Hero concept does not sell the game to you, then maybe the races will. There are 16 different races, each with unique troops and abilities to really add variety and replayability. Although some units are shared by races, you'll be impressed with the selection given here! To add to this, each race has a unique titan that can really change the tide of battle.Titans are units that can only be built near end match when most upgrades have been researched. After it is available, it takes a while to build and if it dies, its gone for the match. However, Titans can mow down armies without flinching, provided they don't get overwhelmed! (If you don't like this concept there is an option to turn this off, but why would you?)Finally, the campaign is truly something to behold. Loads of side missions and ambushes add for a significant amount of reputability. The mainline of the campaign is not all that exciting and ends quickly but the significant amount of side mission will more than make up for the weakness of the mainline in the campaign. The missions are also quite varied too. Tournament pitting you Warlord vs others as well as defense missions and elimination missions leave the campaign quite varied.Although my overall view of this game is highly positive, I would be boldly lying if I did not say there were problems with the game as well. Bugs that were very annoying in the first game have made a return here. I experienced an average of ""1 crash every hour"", but most came from multiplayer. I am unsure if what was causing the issues but it was a problem for both Windows 8 and 10. Low max resolution can be a little annoying to some as well (although it didn't bother me at all).The most important problem by far though is the AI in Warlords Battlecry series. Sometimes you will start a match and the AI will be vicious. They will quickly swarm you and be relentless for quite some time, even on easy difficulty. This can be fun at times but frustrating as well. Other times, The AI will suddenly refuse to continue on and just give up or make baffling mistakes. I watched the AI walk a Titan into a field of towers and let it die. Afterwards, maybe 10 minutes later, it brought an army that wiped the board in seconds without losing many casualties. The AI also makes VERY bad decisions with their Warlords which will handicap them (but to a lesser extent). Suffice it to say that the AI is definitely passable and a capable challenge, but could benefit from a little work.The good+ Warlords+ Retinue of generals+ Loads of varying Classes+ Loads of different Races+ Titans add a new level of combat+ More fleshed out mechanics+ Building art style is nice+ Soundtrack is decent (and easily modifiable if you want to make a custom soundtrack)The Bad- Still filled with some annoying bugs- Crashes are horribly common (I would go hours without having one, then have 3 in 10 minutes)- Random AI can sometimes be REALLY hard or REALLY easy.- At times, maps are not optimized for the AI to understand. (Some maps cause the AI to become brain dead)- Max resolution is 1280x1024 (which you get used to quickly but still should have higher resolution available)- The fan made patches for this game are forcefully implemented here. (It is obvious that Steam and GOG did not spend any time playing the game as one mod adds a silly profane comment when building conversion occurs.) This is not a deal breaker, especially with this game, but I hate when stuff like this happens. I want the option to mod me vanilla game, not be given a premoded version.Overall, I give this game a 9/10 and recommend it for Warlords series fans. Its a good strategy game for anyone but its massive compilation of Warlords units (especially from Warlords 4) was awesome. This game is rough around the edges and some support would really help smooth out the problems. None of the problems I encountered were ever bad enough to make me upset with the game. If you're thinking about this, give it a go!"
