76561198027269099,Recommended,433280,23233127,"Posted: 27 May, 2016",all,Lance L,"I'm recommending this game with a warning: it's fan-modded, and it sometimes crashes to the desktop in the middle of your game, which can be maddening.  I've experienced other odd, one-off bugs from time to time, like being declared victorious when the enemy kills my hero instead of other way 'round, and unusual unit behavior occasionally.  But I was such a huge, drooling fanboy of WBII, which sadly is not offered on Steam, that I had to pick up WBIII for 10 bucks.  It's not all that different from WBII and still contains all the elements that made the original great: persistent heroes, different races to lead (with genuine differences in gameplay), towers that you can occupy to make them stronger (wish AOE had that), and no-fuss resource gathering which again you can strengthen permanently by adding workers (though ""permanent"" assumes the enemy won't convert your resource).  There is also some really good assignable AI for your units, with an unusually large number of choices, from RAMPANT (stomp around the map attacking everything) to GUARD to FALLBACK 25% HEALTH and PATROL and so many more.  The only time the game really gets fidgety is when the enemy and you keep converting the same set of resources over and over and over, at which point you really have to just break the cycle and start making advanced units to go wipe him out.TL;DR?A really good RTS in its day, with some unique features that make it still a blast to play.  This version is fan-modded and sometimes quirky, sometimes buggy.  For $10 it was a no-brainer for me, but modern gamers with no history wth the game may find it quaint and dated."
